The paper is about autonomous learning in robotics, specifically in the context of tendon-driven systems. Therefore, cs.RO (Robotics) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the use of artificial neural networks and reward-driven exploration, which are common techniques in machine learning and artificial intelligence, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also draws inspiration from biological systems, indicating that cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) may also be a relevant sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the versatility of the algorithm in adapting to changes in the environment and target task, suggesting that cs.SY (Systems and Control) may also be a relevant sub-category.
